{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Add focused prerequisite consistency review\n\n## Goal\nEvaluate whether a ticket plan remains consistent with each direct prerequisite without injecting prerequisite material into general reviewers or changing existing parent and child review behavior.\n\n## Upstream contract\nThis story implements against the certified material-pin interface from `75de-02b0-d454-410b` and the certified review-phase interface from `5967-4476-7f9f-442d`. The pin interface supplies one review-time `PlanRelationSnapshot` preload keyed by authoritative canonical ticket ID, including relation kind, readable state, pinned material, and the ticket plan text needed by review. This story neither recollects relations nor changes parent and child handling.\n\n## Implementation\n- Register one prerequisite-consistency criterion. It runs only when the shared `PlanRelationSnapshot` preload succeeded and contains readable direct `depends_on` or inverse `blocks` prerequisites. The same canonical ticket ID appearing through both relations is evaluated once.\n- Extend the production Pass-1 batch runner with a prerequisite-only route. It receives the subject plan plus stable-order whole prerequisite blocks from the single preload, packs as many blocks as fit, and invokes the dedicated `plan_review_prerequisite_coverage` structured-output contract. General criterion requests receive only the existing subject and criterion inputs.\n- Define measurable isolation: capture every emitted request in the integration test and assert that each non-prerequisite finder and verifier system prompt, user prompt, and instructions contain neither a prerequisite canonical ID nor prerequisite plan text from the preload. Also assert exactly one relation preload supplies both pin creation and prerequisite routing.\n- Add `_prerequisite_coverage_model()` in `passes.py` and register it as `contracts.register_contract(\"plan_review_prerequisite_coverage\", _prerequisite_coverage_model)`. Its output is `records: list[PrerequisiteCoverageRecord]`. Each record is `{prerequisite_id: canonical string, disposition: consistent|finding|indeterminate, findings: list[Finding], reason_code?: evaluation-error|output-invalid|attribution-invalid, detail?: string}`.\n- Require exactly one record per readable pinned canonical ID. `consistent` requires no findings or reason code. `finding` requires at least one finding and no reason code, with every finding carrying that same canonical `prerequisite_id`. `indeterminate` requires no findings and one closed-enum reason code; detail is optional and non-authoritative. Missing, duplicate, unknown-ID, parse-invalid, or schema-invalid output maps the affected bin to `output-invalid`. Failed or unprovable canonical attribution maps the affected prerequisite to `attribution-invalid`. Provider or model failure maps the affected bin to `evaluation-error`. Indeterminate records never assert incompatibility.\n- Keep batching semantically neutral. Every prompt asks for independent subject-to-one-prerequisite judgments and forbids cross-prerequisite findings. Stable bins contain whole blocks only; neither the subject nor a prerequisite is split. A conflict in the last stable-order block is evaluated identically to a singleton call.\n- Size the actual prerequisite prompt topology, including system prompt, subject plan, prerequisite blocks, output reserve, and headroom, through a new prerequisite-specific budget adapter in `sizing.py`; do not assume the parent-plus-children constants fit unchanged. On a context-limit error, split a failing stable-order bin into contiguous halves recursively. Escalate a singleton through `models_at_or_above()`. Exhaustion at the largest window emits its record as `indeterminate/evaluation-error` with `detail=input-too-large`. Non-context provider failure emits `indeterminate/evaluation-error` for every unresolved ID in that bin.\n- Extend findings with optional `prerequisite_id`. Add `prerequisite_attribution_valid` to the shared `Binary` model in `review_kernel/verify_models.py`; it defaults to `na`, joins `_BINARY_NA_DEFAULT`, and is excluded from `GRADED_BINARY`, so it is a veto rather than a validity contributor. Pass 2 sets `yes` only when the indexed prerequisite finding names the exact canonical ID in its source bin, `no` for wrong or unprovable attribution, and `na` for non-prerequisite findings. Pass 3 preserves the ID on upheld findings and drops attribution=`no` as unsupported; missing or malformed verification leaves that finding INDETERMINATE. Reuse the phase story threshold function and existing decide path.\n- Thread `prerequisite_coverage` through both workflow branches into `plan_review_decide` and `plan_review_coach`. `plan_review_decide` validates record completeness before partitioning and adds affected records to the indeterminate partition. `plan_review_coach` sets `coverage.prerequisite_indeterminate=true` when any record is indeterminate. In `orchestrator.finalize_verdict`, check that flag before all PASS or BLOCK branches and force top-level `INDETERMINATE`. The existing signing boundary in `plan_review.__init__` signs only PASS, so this result is necessarily unsigned and cannot be certified.\n- Add a dedicated `prerequisite_fidelity_report` in `parity.py`; leave `ItemRecord`, `CONTAINER_CRITERIA`, `attribution_accuracy`, and `container_fidelity_report` unchanged. The new report reuses general recall and false-acceptance calculations but scores attribution with prerequisite records as `pred_prerequisite_id == gold_prerequisite_id` over authoritative canonical IDs.\n- Add new opt-in `prerequisite_packing_spot_eval` coverage in `fidelity_spot_eval.py` with at least eight gold sets of at least three prerequisites: two all-consistent, two single-conflict, two tail-conflict where the conflict is last in stable bin order, one attribution-confusion, and one multi-bin case. Compare packed calls with one-prerequisite-per-call. Packed finding recall may not decrease, false acceptance may not increase, every readable ID must have one coverage record, and corpus-wide prerequisite attribution errors must be zero. Failure retains smaller bins or singleton calls.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Only the focused prerequisite route receives prerequisite canonical IDs or plan text.\n- [ ] One shared relation preload supplies both material-pin creation and prerequisite routing.\n- [ ] Existing parent and child review behavior is byte-for-byte unchanged when no direct prerequisite route applies.\n- [ ] Stable token-budget batching never splits the subject or a prerequisite block.\n- [ ] Every readable pinned prerequisite receives exactly one closed-schema coverage disposition.\n- [ ] Missing or incorrect canonical-ID attribution cannot produce a blocking finding.\n- [ ] Every upheld prerequisite finding carries its Pass-2-verified authoritative prerequisite ID.\n- [ ] Every indeterminate record uses the closed reason-code enum and has no incompatibility finding.\n- [ ] Any indeterminate prerequisite record forces a top-level unsigned INDETERMINATE verdict even when other findings would BLOCK or PASS.\n- [ ] Largest-window singleton exhaustion emits one `indeterminate/evaluation-error` record with `detail=input-too-large` before top-level remediation.\n- [ ] Captured non-prerequisite prompts contain no prerequisite canonical IDs or prerequisite plan text.\n- [ ] The new opt-in prerequisite fidelity evaluation satisfies the packed-versus-singleton recall, false-acceptance, coverage, and attribution thresholds.\n\n## Verification\n- Run `.venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/unit/test_plan_review_prerequisites.py tests/unit/test_plan_review_passes.py tests/unit/test_plan_review_sizing.py`.\n- Run `.venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/interfaces/llm/test_plan_review_prerequisite_isolation.py tests/interfaces/llm/test_plan_review_workflow.py`.\n- Run the new opt-in prerequisite packing evaluation documented by `fidelity_spot_eval.py` and record its result in a ticket comment.\n- Run `make check` and `.venv/bin/python -m pytest -m \"not integration\"`."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784560452104448001,"uuid":"96054a26-c2f4-46ee-b4cb-646e63f25b37"}